page.title: 01Wykeham forest
page.content: Relatively flat and predominantly coniferous forests in the North York Moors National Park. The forests are in all stages from felled and newly planted areas to mature forest. Most residents live in the small settlement of North Moor and are forestry commission workers,although there are few farms. Arable farming is done to the south of the forests, and along Troutsdale in the north west there is some grazing along the valley. Towards the north the area drops steeply into Troutsdale long the ridge of Troutsdale Brow. From the top of this Brow (e.g. High wood Brow) there are spectacular views to the north. The area is accessible to motorists so is much visited. The forests are also popular with walkers. As there are no facilities the area is restricted to day trips.
